If even one pane is alive (e.g., a hung `sleep` counted as "done" isn't caught here), claimed-file orphans from *other* dead panes are never returned to queue. Partial-death scenarios (some agents die, one survives stuck) leave orphaned tasks permanently claimed until the surviving pane eventually dies.

**B. `ALL_DEAD_SINCE` only arms when `queued == 0 && claimed == 0` (line 284)**
```bash
if $all_done_or_dead && [[ $done_count -lt $TOTAL_TASKS ]] && [[ $queued -eq 0 ]] && [[ $claimed -eq 0 ]]; then
```
The 15-second grace-period counter (`ALL_DEAD_SINCE`) only starts when there are no queued *and* no claimed tasks. But after orphan recovery moves files from `claimed/` → `queue/`, the next loop iteration resets `ALL_DEAD_SINCE=""` (line 291) because `queued > 0` again. This can create a **loop: orphan recovery re-queues → timer resets → timer re-arms → repeat**, potentially delaying the "PARTIAL" completion exit indefinitely if recovery keeps cycling.

**C. No teardown of the tmux session itself**
On `exit 0` (line 397), the monitor exits cleanly but the tmux session `stampede-${RUN_ID}` is never killed or detached. Dead panes and the session linger. No cleanup of `.stampede/$RUN_ID/pids/`, `claimed/`, or temp files.

